Q17:
Pike Place Market is a 70s vibe architecturally that is much less appealing than Westside Market’s turn of the century architecture. Also Pike Place smells more strongly of fish. Pike Place has an underground knick knack/oddities section (unlike Westside), a groceries section like Westside, a restaurant area like Westside, and a crafts section (unlike Westside). The variety at Pike Place makes it feel like it’s catered to tourists rather than for the people of Seattle. At Westside, there are definitely tourists, but also people like me do their regular grocery shopping there because it’s a one stop shop for fresh stuff (I trust the butchers there more than the supermarket, the vegetables on the corner stall are cheap, and the cheese sellers have a great variety, and I can get good FRESH baked bread). If Westside spread itself too thin like Pike Place, expanding into knick knacks/oddities/regular shops it would no longer feel like a place where I could go grocery shopping. Plus it would lose some of its history I think—becoming “over produced.” One thing Pike Place has going for it — great views and great seating, so you can grab a snack and sit to stay a while. The tiny balcony at Westside is FANTASTIC, but when the weather is bad and you can’t go across the street to the park, it is packed. Plus, no tables makes it more difficult to enjoy the delicious snacks I’ve picked up at the market (it’s usually a grocery shopping + snack/meal trip, because there are so many good ready-made food stalls at Westside—-this is unique from a regular grocery shopping trip for me where I usually go ONLY for groceries). 

I usually entice a friend to go with me to Westside by convincing them to try the peruvian purple potato cake (with goat cheese filling) at Orale, but they often wander away and try their own thing. This is the beauty of the market! But the options can be overwhelming. It might be good to have some specific items at specific stands that really are the stars—the multitude of choices can be overwhelming to first-timers. Having maybe 4 products that are really “famous” that people want to try/check off the bucket list — potentially one at each corner of the market to encourage people to explore the whole market along the way — could help first-timers find their footing better, preventing overwhelm.
